<br>Thanks,<br>Traxxus<br>Ranger of Surefall <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ubjond.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Bjond</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/white_redspot.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 369<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(2/5/02 7:01:18 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1286.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> If you're in with experienced players ..</span><hr size=1> .. it's almost always some form of NBG on contested items.  For random coin loot, a regular group will usually do &quot;commie&quot; or &quot;master&quot; loot -- one person loots *everything* with /autosplit off.  Then, at group break, sells and does a /split to share out the coin.<br><br>NBG = need before greed.  Basically, the greater the utility you have for the item, the more chance there is of it defaulting to you.  For example, runed circlet drops in a group of monk, druid, shaman.  The shaman has a better hat already.  So, it automatically goes to the druid.  If the shaman did not have a better, they'd /random on it or maybe one would defer to the other.  The monk isn't even considered for the item.  Need it to trade is considered greed, not need.  Need it for a secondary character is sometimes considered barely above need it to trade, but it's never enough to let you /random against a primary. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uxelenathebard.showPublicProfile?language=EN>XelenaTheBard</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 24<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(2/5/02 7:05:05 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1286.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: What's the best way to devide loot?</span><hr size=1> Best way to do loot - there is a command in game that rolls a die. For smaller groups, it is best to do the following:<br><br>/random 1 100<br><br>Use the numbers to determin who gets it that item, or if it is something that repeatively drops, use them to determin the order.<br><br>For big raids, well, this is how the guild I go to raids with on Test do it like this. The roll for uber items is this:<br><br>&quot;Traditional and class specific loot will be randomed off at 1 to 1,000 with a 50-point bonus per level over 50. Traditional loot and class specific loot will follow a strict &quot;need before greed&quot; basis, if you can and will use you are entitled to roll. If you do win something, you will not be able to roll until everyone of the same class has won something. Please note that last piece rules will be in affect on all class specific pieces with the exception of uber loot, however merit will surpass last piece rules when it comes to breastplates and robes.&quot;<br><br>(So if you are a level 55 character, you would /random 1 1250 for loot.)<br><br>And for the uber loot on raids:<br><br>&quot;Uber loot, that which drops from mini-bosses, etc., will be done by randoming 1 to 1,000 with a 50-point bonus per level over 50 will occur. Winning uber loot will exempt you from traditional and class specific loot. Please do not hesitate to contact us prior to the raid concerning whether or not a particular mob is considered “uber”.&quot;<br><br>And a final added note for big raids:<br><br>&quot;Traditional or class specific loot that does not suit anyone’s “need before greed” situation will be regarded as a “free for all (FFA)” piece. FFA will be randomed at 1 to 1,000 with a 50-point bonus per level over 50. Unlike other loot, winning FFA loot will not exempt you from any category other than future FFA rolls. <br><br>Epic pieces will be done in the priority of a)progress b)level and c)merit.<br><br>Any and all non-nodrop loot, regardless of category will be handled after the raid. This includes gems as well. In the situation you did not win anything the entire raid, gems will be randomed at the end of the raid on a simple 1 to 1,000 basis.&quot;<br><br>Now, as complecated as this all may seem, the guild Silver Circle on Test has used it, and it works well. Depending upon the dungeon, the level 50 + bonus can be changed. Like for places like Unrest it can be set to every level over 20.<br><br>Those are the loot rules I am used to, but it's up to you on whether you like the system. When I get to higher levels, and I run raids, I will probably use this system as it is what I am used to.<br><br>Note: Everything in the &quot; &quot; marks was taken from the Silver Circle message boards last Hate raid post.<br><br> <p>-Xelena<br>Up and Coming Songstress<br>Near Master Fletcher<br>Firiona Vie Server</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uevangelinanife.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Evangelina Nife</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I'm the princess, okay?</span><br>  Posts: 508<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(2/5/02 7:20:44 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1286.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: What's the best way to devide loot?</span><hr size=1>    I prefer the everyone drinks as many short beers as possible, and then the first person to successfully click on the corpse whilst the screen is moving around wins <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br><br>- Syll <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uitchibumbashalots.showPublicProfile?language=EN>ItchibumBashalots</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 300<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(2/5/02 8:00:24 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1286.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: What's the best way to devide loot?</span><hr size=1> Xel that is a very cool system for open raids and even guild raids if they choose to go that way.<br><br>My old guild had a point system that weighed heavy on merit and NB4G.<br><br>Now as far as pick up groups I am very much a NB4G person but I am also realistic.  There are many places where certain classes aint gettin much.<br><br>It is also a case of trust.  I try to group with people I can trust or know when we go item hunting or what have ya.<br><br>Other than that its main loot and split after.<br><br>My classic example of the exception is the King camp in OS.  How many casters are you going to get if you dont roll for the items that drop there.  I was in that camp on the old server and a bracer dropped two of the times i was there.  I lost both rolls....killed me as an ogre warrior to loose but I didnt fuss.  One guy was a warrior....didnt need shrink but hey its a cool bracer.  The other Im sure sold it for 50k or traded it for a lodi shield or whatever....was fair.  He put the time in, did the camp.  He didnt offer it to me but I wouldnt have bought it either.  I wanted to loot my own.  I did eventually get one and the wife even got a fungi tunic on a roll.<br><br>It really depends on the situation.<br><br>As everyone who has ever posted on this subject has said the most important thing to do is to establish it from the get go how it is handled and ALWAYS be fair.  The orc pick you fight over today could cost you the King group you wanted to get into and cant because you were unfair on loot way back when you were level 5.<br><br>Hope it helps.<br><br>Ichi <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/umystikatfv.showPublicProfile?language=EN>MystikatFV</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 7<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(2/5/02 8:38:56 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1286.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: What's the best way to devide loot?</span><hr size=1> You tell 'em Ichi. <br><br>I am also a huge proponent of NBG but realize that at times you just have to grin, bear it, and let everyone roll.<br><br>Different servers have different thresholds for this. On regular servers, unfortunately, greed outweighs need more often due to the value of items on the player market. Like Xelena, I came here from Test where there is no economy to speak of and need usually trumps greed. FV seems to me to be somewhere in the middle...hopefully closer to the Test way.<br><br>The most important thing is that policy be agreed to by all BEFORE the goodies drop.<br><br>At low levels where coin loot is more of an issue, /autosplit is problematic. It doesn't make change. If a mob drops 4pp 10gp 20sp 40cp, in a group of six, the looter gets 4pp 5gp 5sp 10cp and everyone else gets 0pp 1gp 3sp 6cp. Not much of a split, is it? If you get into a group where one person pounces on every corpse, justifying it with &quot;but I have split turned on&quot;, reach for the Disband button.<br><br>-- Mystikat, Dar Khura with zero tolerance for hogs<br> <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ukisarintenamin.showPublicProfile?language=EN>KisarinTenamin</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 15<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(2/5/02 9:37:32 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1286.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: What's the best way to devide loot?</span><hr size=1> I am a big fan of NBG, though I have not gotten into any situations where it really mattered (not of that level,  yet).<br><br>As I am reading XelenaTheBard's post, however, one thing puzzles me.  What is the justification for raising the cap above a certain level?  looking up from below that looks like nothing more than discrimination.  Is there a real reasonfor it?  Or did that add on just develop as a result of someone coming up with a clever way to give their high level friends a better chance at the best stuff?  That is what it looks like to me... Not really fair to those who have risked more in the raid (risked more because they ARE lower and therefore have a higher chance of dying).<br><br>At the lower levels I am at now, however, we don't need to get so complicated.  Usually it is either FFA (which I always loose out at because I am busy for the first 3 seconds after the battle with switching songs and instruments) of Alphabetically.  Alpha loot works out all right, especially if it is combined with /rand for important, less common stuff.  You just have to have one person who takes responsability to call out the turns so that everyone knows. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ubjond.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Bjond</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/white_redspot.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 371<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(2/5/02 10:48:43 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1286.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Oh wow</span><hr size=1> I can't believe anyone but a fat warrior rolled for a shrink bracer or was permitted to roll.  Since I'm typically the puller &amp; group leader, this kind of problem usually doesn't come up in my groups.  If it was anothers', I'd walk -- no puller usually means no group.  I just can't tolerate that kind of greed.  What is he going to do?  Win random, then do /gsay &quot;hey fatboy, wanna buy a bracer?&quot;  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br><br>Of course, if there are no fat warriors and no small warriors, then it's open.  Same for fungi-tunic -- default to monks, then other classes that would use (it's pretty much top chest in game for monks and only a twink or situational for others by that level).  Just because you're in an area that doesn't drop loot for your class is no excuse to put yourself into random for something you'd trade.  There are plenty of spots where it will be an item for you and not others; what goes around comes around.  Do a greed /random and you won't be able to get help on your camps.  Guess I was lucky on my old server.  There were enough of us that felt strongly about this that some would end up horribly shunned if they were greedy.  I recall one cleric that would sit in Karnor's LFG auc'ing for groups while groups would auc for a cleric.  No one would touch him.<br><br>BTW, a comment on the level issue Kisarin brought up.  At a raid that needs level 55-60 players, lower levels contribute very little to the effort.  If they die, it's small loss to the group.  You have to work to a lot harder keep them alive and to educate them.  Each level above 50 is similar in power to about 5-10 levels below 50.  Also, it's a simple way to gauge seniority when you don't know how much time everyone has put in helping out others (sort of a bonus for time-in-grade and a way to doge the whole &quot;but I'm more senior than you!&quot; issue). <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ublakkon.showPublicProfile?language=EN>blakkon</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 78<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(2/5/02 11:28:51 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1286.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Oh wow</span><hr size=1> NBG works best in guild or friend groups.  Otherwise, it usually has to be random or masterloot (depending on the drops).  For important camps I would very rarely (read never) get into a pickup group.  If I did the loot rules would be established early on.  If I &quot;win&quot; a roll for something soemone else can use, often it just goes to them anyways.<br><br>If I had a dime for every pickup planes or dragon raid where class X whines that they didn't get to roll, while class Y did.... Clearly established loot rules are a requirement no matter how unfair, biased, or just plain random they are, if you don't like  the rules find another raid, or group, or whatever.<br><br>Just so you know <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   Loot schemes are one of the more debated things on every server message board.... <p>Lorec <br>Wandering Judge of the Tribunal <br>Excellent Tailor <br>Master Baker <br>Lousy Smith <br>Master Brewer <br>Master  Drunk <br>Aspiring Polyglot <br>Wannabe Alchemist <br></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/usliver123.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Sliver123</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 44<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(2/6/02 3:28:08 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1286.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Oh wow</span><hr size=1> The method I like is when a master looter loots all items and cash (make sure it is someone you can trust) and at the end of the group or when members leave/join, is to /split the cash, and /random 100. Highest roll picks an item, second picks the next, thrid next and so on. <br>Pre-empting that is if someone can use an item and it would be an upgrade, they get it. If 2 or more are in the same boat, roll and pick.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uveloxiavoluptuous.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Veloxia Voluptuous</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 297<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(2/6/02 3:37:06 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1286.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Oh wow</span><hr size=1> WOW Sliver.... in my 3 years of EQ, i have never seen roll and pick as an addition to NBG(or without NBG). I think i will use that in my future groups! seems alot more fair than winning a little item, then a big item drops and you cant roll... and alot simpler than rolling on the 2nd item and if you win, giving up the 1st item to be rolled on again. in places like Seb Crypt... that gets frustrating. <p><BR><B>Veloxia Voluptuous </B><BR>45 Halfling warrior<BR>"Even the smallest person can change the course of the future" ~ Gandalf<BR>*gnaws another enemy kneecap to shreds*<BR>Veloxia@hotmail.com</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uimogenelddar.showPublicProfile?language=EN>ImogenElddar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 141<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(2/6/02 3:43:24 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1286.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> loot dogma</span><hr size=1> Human nature being what it is, I can assure you of a few things:<br><br>1) Just about any system you can possibly image, somebody uses, another person advocates passionately, and somebody else despises.<br><br>2) There are almost as many systems as there are players, and though many of them are so similar as to be nearly indistinguishable to you or I, the proponents of each system will insist that the differences are crucial.<br><br>3) Everybody insists that their system is &quot;more fair&quot; than every other system.<br><br>4) People spend a lot of time arguing over which system is best, and tend to get quite angry when you don't agree with them.<br><br>5) The arguments tend to devolve into personal attacks, usually along the lines of, &quot;You don't like my system because you're selfish and you want a system that gives your class an unfair advantage!&quot;<br><br>6) As of yet, nobody has actually produced any concrete evidence that their system is, in the long run, any better or more fair than pure randomness.<br><br>7) It's rather like religion, when you get right down to it. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ugenththetiger.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Genth the Tiger</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 39<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(2/6/02 3:55:02 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1286.topic&index=12>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: loot dogma</span><hr size=1> what i find works best.<br>1. Have a master looter<br>2. When someone leaves everyone rolls 1-100.<br>3. Their number determines the order in which they pick an item from what was recieved in loot. <br>4. repeat if everyone gets and item and more loot is left. <br><br>This works great for camps where there are lots of drops like Velks village etc.  and with this server being all NO DROP i'd think it would be ideal for any camp really. <br><br>Genth <br>Khala Dun of the 38th rank <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ugenththetiger.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Genth the Tiger</A> at: 2/6/02 12:56:34 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ubraellarth.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Braellarth</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 62<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(2/6/02 5:03:51 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1286.topic&index=13>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: loot dogma</span><hr size=1> There are flaws in each system, doesnt make them bad.. but makes some rules better situational.<br><br>NBG - need before greed. only problem is that certain spots have no items for xxx class, or are set up specifically for one class only. Take Drolvag captain. Mostly warrior items... so you have to draw the line when you create the group or invite new people.. NBG in drolvag captain is on the verge of selfishness and explotiation of other class's.<br>Do you make a rule like: warriors nbg on the cobolt (warrior kunark class armour) and jade mace free for all, cloak ffa (cloak is'nt that great and it's so common everyone gets one after there first hunt in this spot)<br><br>Defining rules and inform people if you know what 'might' drop, so that they know what they are getting into, if you dont know and no one in group knows.. Nbg is good but evaluate what you get at the end of a night, as a puller and tank i put my life on the line a lot more than some of the other classes, risking my life on extreemly dangerouse splitting, then tanking or agro mangement.. sometimes i will end up with nothing from the night, i dont mind Ngb at all.. but sometimes i get royally screwed over, since i have melee and magic.. often items goto the 'pure' prime class before hybrids, so i have been completely screwed with Nbg before... a fair group and nbg is perfect, but dont go useing it as a means of exploitation, earns you a worse reputation imho! (greed to the extreem)<br><br>Port/split - great, but i have had evacers ld, come back then port without me, or hold items for me while i am pulling/splitting and not give them back.. had the same person litteraly take around 5 quest gems for veliouse armour that way.. but everyone says 'she's a great druid!' so rather than complain i stick up with it.. happens again. Now this is a occurence with one person i had on my last server... but it scares me when i do this with people i dont know, i have a fear of evacers looting now.. only use this with people you trust, it can be mis-used and people can get away with it.<br><br>ticket - ticket system is like a raffle, all roll /seed and one with highest picks from list... works perfect in places like the cypt in sebilis where you can come out with 2-3 class items, 2-4 misc items and a few gems.<br>Now i love this method, works best when you all know the value of an said item, some people are more interested in selling items so will pick the most expensive or 'easyest' item to sell, others will pick an item for a friend or an item they can use, while back i had option of picking a second bloodember bracer or one of the other nice items including heiro cloak. i chose the bracer (+16 ac) because i already had one, and i had a fairly nice cloak, not as nice.. but the others with me had worse cloaks so i picked bracer, i was happy with it, other guys were happy with it... where's the problem? there isnt one, i like this method, its more of a compromise of what you want and what others want, good when there are no items that can really be NBG.<br><br> <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ubjond.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Bjond</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/white_redspot.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 378<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(2/6/02 5:09:21 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1286.topic&index=14>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Roll and pick ..</span><hr size=1> .. is really nice.  I think I recall using it once in old sebelis jail area (very rich drop area).  Most items people want aren't dropable by the time they reach the truly contested stage (planar/god/dragon loot), so you can't hold them for later roll/pick.  With the lack of no-drops on FV, it sounds like a truly great method for this server.<br><br>I'd probably modify it to include immediate rolls/defaults for things that people would put on and wear right away.  That's the best part of any loot drop anyway -- watching a friend get a nice upgrade and putting it on. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uqixxfv.showPublicProfile?language=EN>QixxFV</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Thats not my tail</span><br>  Posts: 73<br> <font 